What you need to know about Yoko, the fierce beast, is that save for her two little fangs she has no teeth. That’s another story. But she is nonetheless fearless and dangerous. I bid her farewell tomorrow as she journeys with my fierce daughter back to California. I do love a cat.

@viviennewestwood has left the building.  I love fashion, although I really know very little about it. I just know what makes me feel good. Vivienne’s clothes rocked my world when I discovered her in the 80’s. She was punk and she was glamorous and her tailoring was second to none.  Once I started making money and was being sent abroad to promote myself I finally got me some Westwood. London wasn’t London without a trip to her shop. All the pieces pictured in this post I have owned; the corset, the platforms, the tartan skirt suit, the pearl orb choker. Collectibles now. To me she is as young as I was when I bought those clothes and always will be. A curtsy to you, Dame Viv.
Another trip around the sun. Water = Happy Place. 🪅🎈🎉

It’s widely known that a cat can be adorable and sweet one minute and suddenly possessed the next. Yoko exemplifies this perfectly here. You can see, as she unleashes her wrath, her lone four fangs. She has no other teeth but that is of no concern to her. She will cut you just the same.
@sarahjarosz and @marc_cohn and I just sat down to rehearse. Then we heard. I can’t speak. No one can. But we’re gonna sing. Love you, Croz.

Greetings fine people!  @marc_cohn and @sarahjarosz and I are on the road through March and we would so love to see y’all somewhere.  We’re all onstage together for the evening and I must tell you what a joy it is for me to play and sing with these stellar musicians (and they’re really nice folks, too). You can access our itinerary and get tix on any of our websites. Come on down! 🎶 🎸 🎹 🎤 🚌
FAKE ACCOUNT.  Please don’t follow!

Tomorrow we’ll be at the @benaroyahall with @marc_cohn and @sarahjarosz! 
We hope to see you in Seattle!

#OnThisDate Five years ago, my album “The Starlighter” was released! To celebrate, I just released the complete, animated music video on YouTube. Four of the eight videos from this were released separately back in 2018. Now, I present to a clip from it for “The Journey”. Watch the full video on my YouTube channel! 📺

Starlighter, my second record of lullabies with arrangements from the book ‘Lullabies and Night Songs’ was released five years ago today, produced by the amazing Doug Petty (as was the first lullaby record, called Holiday Songs and Lullabies). This is Jeff Young, an amazing keyboard player and singer I had the privilege to know and perform with.  There are so many mourning his loss today.  Not only was he an incredible musician, but one of the best guys you’d ever hope to know.  He toured and recorded with Jackson, Bonnie, Sting, Donald Fagen and, for a while, me. He was so loved and will be terribly missed. Thank you for being you, Jeff. I’m so sad, but I’m smiling just remembering your laugh.

More memories! 25 years ago today @johnleventhal and I received Grammy awards for Song of the Year (songwriter’s award) and Record of the Year (producer’s award). The song was Sunny Came Home and we certainly never saw it coming! John and I only wrote the album to please ourselves, but I guess you just never know. I love playing Sunny every night I perform. She took us places I never could have imagined!

#TBT
I joined this band, The Dixie Diesels, in 1975 when I was 19 years old. We took off out of Carbondale, Illinois, bound for Austin shortly after I joined up. I’d never lived anywhere that my parents didn’t and it was a big deal. As you may know, I ended up back in ATX over 25 years ago which gives you an idea of how much I loved it.

This photo was taken in Carbondale just prior to our exodus. From L to R:

Kirk - our then-roadie (who did not come with us.)
Brad Davis - our fearless leader on guitar and vocals
Me - girl singer 
Mike Potter - bass
Charlie Morrill - drums
Rusty “Radar” Hurst - guitar and pedal steel
Willy Wainwright - fiddle (seated)
Unknown Gentleman (sorry, sir!) - (seated)

So began my tenure with “boys in vans” as we traveled the southwest, pulling in $25 each a night for a four-set show, and I’ve been a touring musician ever since. I ended up in NYC in 1980, no longer a Diesel, but that is another story for another time. #roaddog

#dixiediesels #throwback #throwbackthursday #carbondaleillinois #oldschoolcool #backintheday #blackandwhitephoto #memories #inthe70s

It’s Music Monday so I thought I’d offer up a live version of “Tennessee”. This is from a solo concert I did at The Paradiso in Amsterdam in 2007. You can find the whole show on my YouTube channel; it’s called The Lost Concert and I remember it well. I was touring Europe that fall. Along for the ride was my boyfriend who was breaking up with me. I went onstage every night in a trance and thought for sure I was doing a terrible job. But I think this concert proves me wrong and it reminds me that some of our best performances come from situations where we are so emotionally spent, usually due to exhaustion or grief or both, that we feel like we’re on auto-pilot, yet upon reflection we might find a lot of depth in these performances. I think maybe the reason for this is that in our pain we become stripped of ego and artifice and our exposed hearts are all we have left - the same true and vulnerable hearts that conjured up the songs in the first place. There’s nowhere to hide, and sometimes that is a gift. Anyway, I hope you enjoy it.

#shawncolvin #tennessee #paradiso #paradisoamsterdam #amsterdam #inconcert #thelostconcert #onstage #liveperformance #soloperformance #acousticguitar #acousticversion #musicmonday #musiconmonday #livemusic #newfolk #backin2007

#TBT - 1996 stint on Letterman. Everybody thinks “Get Out Of This House” is a divorce song. It isn’t! In fact, it is a buyer’s remorse song, inspired by the purchase of my first home. One day, while trying to write, I looked out my window at Lake Austin and felt guilty that I wasn’t awestruck by the view or riding a bike up the hill on my street. Oh why oh why had I left New York?? Now I had a bloody mortgage! Renting had been easy! I couldn’t walk to a deli! My neighbors were doctors and lawyers! It was QUIET! Horror! So there you have it. If anything, I was chastising myself for being so dumb. And now, 27 years later, where am I? Austin, of course!

#GetOutOfThisHouse #LivePerformance #LateShow #Throwback #ThrowbackThursday
@marc_cohn and me finishing up the show in St.  Louis last night with a @leonardcohen beauty called “Hey, That’s No Way To Say Goodbye”.

To celebrate the late, great Gerry Rafferty’s birthday, here’s my version of “Baker Street”. This is on my Uncovered record and sweet @thedavidcrosby did me the honor of singing harmony on it. I kind of darkened it up, as I tend to do, but I felt the lyrics did allow for it. For example, instead of the soaring sax part, we have Milo Deering playing some spooky pedal steel. The original was used to great effect (I thought) in the film, Good Will Hunting. Classic song for the ages.

#GerryRafferty #BakerStreet #DavidCrosby #HappyBirthday #GoodWillHunting #MiloDeering

#TBT 1997
Here’s “Kill The Messenger” from a great series filmed in NYC called Sessions at West 54th Street. The song is off Fat City, my second record, and was inspired by my ardor for Jane Siberry.

Accompanying me are Larry Klein on bass, who produced Fat City, and Steuart Smith on guitar, who was featured on much of the album. 

This was a special, special time for me. Larry, Steuart, and I, were quite the gang, onstage and off. More joy and laughter could not have been had, I swear. All play, no work. Dear, passionate, hilarious pals. Devoted, superlative artists. And all of us lovers of disturbing and dark films, which made for upbeat bus travel. We still recount these glory days; the memories are vivid, the friendships endure. Love you fellas!

#killthemessenger #sessionsatwest54th #larryklein #steuartsmith #liveperformance #inthe90s #throwback #throwbackthursday

Wishing a very Happy 84th Birthday to my friend, Judy Collins. I’ve been listening and covering and imitating Judy since the 60’s, thanks to my parents’ love of her artistry. I wanted to sing like her, play guitar and piano like her. Because of her, I heard songs by Leonard Cohen, Bob Dylan, Stephen Stills, Phil Ochs, Joan Baez, Joni Mitchell, Stephen Sondheim. More importantly, I listened to the incredible songs that Judy wrote, like “My Father”, “Born to the Breed”, “Song For Martin”.

Here we are at the Metropolitan Museum of Art in July of 2012, duetting on her splendid song, “Since You’ve Asked”, just me and Judy and her piano. It was one of the thrills of my life. I know her voice like the back of my hand. My parents were, of course, beside themselves, which was really the best thing of all. We never could have imagined this. (Well, maybe I did.)

Thank you, Judy, for a dream come true, for your work and inspiration, for continuing to hit the road to keep sharing your magic with us. I long to follow in your footsteps. Born to the breed. ❤️

#judycollins #sinceyouveasked #liveperformance #metropolitanmuseumofart #happybirthday #happybday #musicmonday

When I saw the Talking Heads film, “Stop Making Sense”, I was bowled over. I wanted to cover something of theirs, but was stumped. I knew “Psycho Killer” wouldn’t fly. “Naive Melody” was a love song, but maybe too cute.  Hmmmm.

I decided to take a close look at the lyrics just for the hell of it. Well! Talk about depth! The coolest, sweetest love song I’d ever heard. I decided to try it.

I slowed it down (as I tend to do). It turned into a kind of lullaby. I just call it “Home”, and it fills me up every time I sing it. Who knew?

Happy Birthday, David Byrne, and thank you.

#DavidByrne #HappyBirthday #naivemelody

#MusicMonday - Here’s me and Mary Chapin Carpenter doing Greg Brown’s “One Cool Remove” on Later with Jools Holland - I know not when! Greg has always been one of my very favorite songwriters. I opened for him at Club Passim in 1988 maybe? Fell in love. 

This tune is on “Cover Girl”. MCC was good enough to duet with me. We made a video for it, too. I wanted us both to wear white velvet dresses, like angels, but she thankfully put the kabosh on that. When we tour together this song is a mainstay. Thank you, Greg. 💓

#OneCoolRemove #MaryChapinCarpenter

#MusicMonday:
Honoring Glen Campbell whose birthday is today. For me, he is one of the most inspiring and brilliant singers and players ever. 

I’m choosing an alt version of Galveston to share. It’s from a live album Glen made with the incomparable Jimmy Webb called “In Session”. Jimmy also wrote Wichita Lineman (and so many more incredible songs) for Glen. What they do together is perfection. 

This version of Galveston is slower and it aches. You know how I love that. The entire album is profound.

#glencampbell #jimmywebb #galveston #insession #liveversion

It’s the late, great Doc Pomus’s birthday today. He would have been 98 years old. I want to pay tribute to him, not only because he is legendary, but for personal reasons, too. In my early New York City days (1981 or so) Doc took notice of me at Kenny’s Castaways one night. He loved going to clubs around town to check out new acts. He introduced himself and told me, “You can holler!” I must’ve been fronting a band that night, covering songs like “Ring Your Bell” by The Band. Doc took me under his wing. I visited him in his apartment up on West 72nd Street many times, usually on Sunday mornings and most likely hungover. Doc would order in food - he was mostly bedridden - and regale me with great stories and bestow loving and sage advice on me. He would give me lyrics and instruct me to write some music for them, although I didn’t compose songs at the time. But he gave me a chance to try. The only one I ever completed was called, “Had To Find Out For Myself”, and Doc thought it was….ok. Lol. One day he brought Dr. John in to accompany me on electric piano while I sang a new song of Doc’s called, “The Next Heart You Break”. Poor Mac was doing Doc a favor, but I still have the cassette and I have to say: It’s really good! He was a loving and honest mentor and a true champion of rubes like me. Here’s to you, Doc Pomus, with all my love and respect.

#docpomus #youaremissed

Today I’d like to share a snippet of a duet I was blessed to record with the inimitable late Tony Bennett. (You can check out the whole video on YouTube.) It’s of a great old standard called, “Young At Heart”, written by Johnny Richards and Carolyn Leigh.  What can I say? Tony was a master, wasn’t he? We recorded it live at the Capital Records Building in LA with an orchestra conducted by Nelson Riddle. It doesn’t get any more legendary than that! To say I was scared…is an understatement. Mr. Bennett was so very kind and encouraging - he even sketched a little drawing of me. I did my best to hold my own, but I credit Tony with making me sound like I might’ve known what I was doing. He had more than enough elegance to go around, and made it all seem kind of effortless. Hats off to you, Tony Bennett, and the joy you will forever bring.

#tonybennett #youngatheart #itcouldhappentoyou #musicvideo #youwillbemissed

I came across this picture in my photos just now. I made a cover record called Uncovered a few years ago. @thedavidcrosby happened to be in Austin at that time. He was playing at the The Paramount Theater. I went early to hang with him, and took him to Whole Foods after soundcheck - he wanted tangerines. Back in the dressing room we just blabbed and laughed. I did have a bit of an agenda, though. I covered “Baker Street” by Gerry Rafferty. I knew Croz would nail a harmony.  Crosby championed me as soon as Steady On came out, and continued to do so through the years. I figured I had a good shot at enticing him to come sing. Well, he didn’t hesitate. What l learned about him as I got to know him  is that he lived and breathed music. There was never a time he wasn’t writing, recording, touring, tracking down new talent to collaborate with. And he kept that up until he passed away. He literally couldn’t NOT be a musician and a writer and a singer. He loved it all.  He came to the studio the next day. He sang that harmony as though he had always known it, he didn’t even learn it, really. He heard the melody and just sang the harmony. On the spot. Notes perfectly chosen, phrasing in the pocket, blended with me like we were related. Croz always wanted to write songs together but his tunings and chords were way over my hairdo. They are nuts. It never happened. Once I offered him a title to start with. It was so bad I won’t even reveal it here, but I told it to Croz and held my breath. His eyes began to squint and twinkle, you could see the signs of a smile underneath that mustache as his cheeks got round and happy. And I thought - oh! - this is a good sign!  And then, chuckling, he made a sound like one you’d hear on The Voice or something. A nasty, nasal buzzer that meant you sucked. That was David. He said what he thought. Sometimes he got flak for it. In this instance I was grateful, though. It really was an awful idea. I’d like to talk more about him, about the last time I saw him. Insta won’t let me go on - too many words. I’ll get to it, though. SLC

Today is Judee Sill’s birthday. She would’ve been 79 years old. I first heard her when I was 15 while scooping ice cream at Baskin-Robbins in Carbondale, Illinois. Our college radio station, WTAO, was playing in the background when I was suddenly rooted to the spot upon hearing a song called, “There’s A Rugged Road”, by someone named Judee Sill. I bought both of her albums. She sounded entirely unique to me, one of those artists the defies any particular genre. There are folk, gospel, blues, and even classical influences. She tragically died at age 35, but the legacy she left in those two records is sublime and timeless.

#judeesill #youaremissed #theresaruggedroad

It’s #MusicMonday and I’d like to share a recording I made in 1989 of “Have Yourself A Merry Little Christmas”.

First, a little backstory:

As my first album, Steady On, was being finished my record label at the time, Columbia, was eager to have me cut a Christmas song for a seasonal compilation. 

Enter the extraordinary bassist, Tommy “T-Bone” Wolk, who had been championing me and @johnleventhal as we made that first record. He and John were old pals and T-Bone spent a lot of time with us at the studio, playing on a few tracks, but mostly just cheering us on like mad. 

When the label asked for the Christmas song I decided I wanted to just sing “Have Yourself A Merry Little Christmas”, without accompanying myself on guitar. “Like Ella or something”, I said (insert huge laugh here). 

Well, there we were in the studio and T-Bone got excited. He piped up and said, “Richard Tee is down the hall! He’ll play piano and I’ll play bass and we’ll do it LIVE!” And that’s what we did. I got to just sing, alright, with the best of the best. 

Rest in Peace, dear Tommy and dear Richard. I can’t believe how lucky I was.

#haveyourselfamerrylittlechristmas #tbonewolk #johnleventhal #richardtee #christmasmusic #christmassong #christmasvibes #christmas2023 #christmas
I bought extra strings of lights for my Christmas tree and, along with “blinking” and “pulsing”, “steady on” is one of the settings. I’ll go with that one! 💡🎄

1998, The Tonight Show. It was my idea to raid the wardrobe room at the studio for PJ’s in honor of all my childhood Christmas Eves.

The idea that Santa would be prowling around the house in the middle of the night scared the shit out of me. I left cookies anyway, I was no fool.

My maternal grandmother always sewed new flannel pajamas for us to sleep in on that night. Grandma was a chain smoker and we loved smelling the smoky pajamas because it felt like she was there. 

#christmasevememories #lovecamedownatchristmas #christmaseve #christmaseve2023 #christmas #jayleno #thetonightshow #25yearsago

Disneyworld, 1998, another Christmas gig. Oh my, if only I had a dollar for every time I’ve been onstage with Justin Timberlake. Lah dee dah. 

I tried to bust some moves with the *NSYNC boys but, alas, not my forte, and there was a SLIGHT age gap - I was 42 and had given birth a few months prior. They accepted me nonetheless. 

Great song by the great Donny Hathaway. 

Wishing you all love and peace, wherever and however you may be. ❤️
